AMOEBIASIS, PHILIPPINES (AGUSAN DEL SUR) (02)
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Mon 11 Dec 2006
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: Gideon (primary references available on request) [edited]
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>

Previous reported outbreaks of amoebiasis
-----------------------------------------
1933 -- an outbreak (1408 cases, 98 fatal) of amoebiasis was reported in
Chicago.
1978 to 1980 -- an outbreak (36 or more cases) of amoebiasis in Colorado
was related to colonic irrigation at a chiropractic clinic
1984 (publication year) -- an outbreak of amoebiasis on an Israeli kibbutz
affected 25 per cent of the population.
1992 (publication year) -- outbreaks of giardiasis and amoebiasis were
reported among Italian tourists staying at a hotel in Phuket, Thailand.
1993 -- an outbreak (207 cases) of combined amoebic and bacillary dysentery
was reported in Taichung, Taiwan.
1997 to 1998 -- an outbreak (298 cases) of bloody diarrhea due to
_Escherichia coli_ O157, shigella. and amoebiasis was reported in the Dja
River region, Cameroon.
1998 -- an outbreak (53 cases of intestinal amoebiasis and 37 of amoebic
abscess) was reported in Tbilisi, Georgia; drinking water was suspected as
the source of the outbreak. It was estimated at the time that 84 000 to 225
000 persons may have been infected. 10 per cent of healthy controls in the
region were seropositive at the time; and 3 per cent were seropositive 6
months later.
1998 -- an outbreak (464 cases) was reported in Taegu, Republic of Korea.
2002 -- an outbreak (216 cases) among Spanish tourists in Punta Cana,
Dominican Republic was ascribed to contaminated water.
2004 (publication year) -- an outbreak (3 cases, including one hepatic
abscess) of presumed autochthonous amoebiasis was reported in a Dutch family.
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
